The preferred standard units and orderOfMagnitude for the reading are defined by the "value" attribute of this mid-level entity. All mid-level entities should have a "value" attribute. In this case, it would specify the standard SI unit of Pascals and an order of magnitude of -3 to indicate milliPascals. The mid-level entity may have other attributes that provide alternate representations of the data (e.g., enumerations, such as "low", "medium", "high") or other details (e.g., the type of precipitation).
Implementations can use other units, but they should be translatable to the standard units with translation errors causing corresponding increases to the accuracy range.

General structure for reporting observed data.
Any PhysicalObject, as defined by the architecture, can report on a number of SensedValues. Each SensedValue is associated with a type (e.g., in this case ambientAirPressure) and a location (e.g., allows reporting of values at different locations when needed; in this example, "ambient" would always have location 0). The type of SensedValue dictates which specialization is used. In the case of ambientAirPressure, the specialized type of SensedValue used would be the SensedAmbientAirPressure. Based on the rules of specialization, this class automatically contains all of the attributes defined within its parents (e.g., value from SensedPressure and accuracy among others from SensedValue). The SensedValue is determined from 1 or more Sensors (which have various attributes not shown here).
While this example focuses on the SensedAmbientAirPressure, it should be able to serve as a general template for most readings of sensed phenomena. I've even included vehicleHeading and vehicleSpeed - but I think Position needs to be handled separately due to differences in confidence and accuracy meta-data.
The lowest specialization of the sensed value is used to unambiguously link the concept to the phenomenon being measured.

properties.name: Position
properties.documentation: Every physical entity has a Position; within the scope of ITS (surface transport), this location should be on the surface of the earth. Physical entities may be able to detect their location via a variety of technologies; many of these will report the location using a GeoLocation, which is known as the geoPosition of the PhysicalEntity.
